  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css" />
</head>
<body>
  <header>
    <!-- Navigation -->
  </header>

  <main>
    <section id="hero">
      <!-- Hero banner -->
    </section>

    <section id="catalog">
      <!-- Product grid -->
    </section>

    <section id="cart">
      <!-- Cart items -->
    </section>

    <section id="checkout">
      <!-- Checkout form -->
    </section>
  </main>

  <footer>
    <!-- Footer info -->
  </footer>

  <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>


---

ðŸŽ¨ 2. CSS (Styling)

This controls colors, layout, fonts, and responsiveness. Save this as style.css.

/* style.css */
body {
  font-family: 'Poppins', sans-serif;
  margin: 0;
  background-color: #fff5f9;
  color: #1a1a1a;
}

header, footer {
  background: #fff;
  padding: 16px;
  text-align: center;
  border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;
}

#hero {
  background: radial-gradient(circle, #ffe3ec, #fff);
  padding: 40px 20px;
  text-align: center;
}

#catalog {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(220px, 1fr));
  gap: 16px;
  padding: 20px;
}

.card {
  background: #fff;
  border: 1px solid #eee;
  border-radius: 12px;
  padding: 12px;
  text-align: center;
}

.btn {
  padding: 10px 14px;
  border-radius: 8px;
  border: none;
  cursor: pointer;
}

.btn-primary {
  background: #d81b60;
  color: #fff;
}

.btn-outline {
  background: #fff;
  color: #d81b60;
  border: 1px solid #d81b60;
}


---

âš™ï¸ 3. JavaScript (Functionality)

This handles cart logic, navigation, and checkout. Save this as script.js.

// script.js
const products = [
  { id: 'p1', title: 'Cherry Signature', price: 28500 },
  { id: 'p2', title: 'Arabian Oud', price: 42000 },
];

let cart = [];

function addToCart(id) {
  const item = cart.find(i => i.id === id);
  if (item) {
    item.qty += 1;
  } else {
    cart.push({ id, qty: 1 });
  }
  renderCart();
}

function renderCart() {
  const cartSection = document.getElementById('cart');
  cartSection.innerHTML = cart.map(item => {
    const product = products.find(p => p.id === item.id);
    return `<div>${product.title} â€” â‚¦${product.price} x ${item.qty}</div>`;
  }).join('');
}

document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  const catalog = document.getElementById('catalog');
  catalog.innerHTML = products.map(p => `
    <div class="card">
      <h3>${p.title}</h3>
      <p>â‚¦${p.price}</p>
      <button class="btn btn-primary" onclick="addToCart('${p.id}')">Add to Cart</button>
    </div>
  `).join('');
});


---

âœ… Next Step:
You can now upload these three files (index.html, style.css, script.js) to a platform like Netlify or GitHub Pages to go live.

Want me to help you plug in your real product list and images next? Just send them over and Iâ€™ll format everything for you.

Nice â€” I took your original snippets and turned them into three ready-to-use files with a few practical upgrades:

What I changed and added
- Product images support and a sample product list you can replace with real data.
- Cart features: add, increase/decrease quantity, remove item, show subtotal & total.
- Cart persistence using localStorage (so the cart survives page reloads).
- Currency formatting for Naira (â‚¦) via Intl.NumberFormat.
- A simple checkout form (client-side validation stub) and a clear-cart after "checkout".
- Small accessibility and responsive improvements (alt text, button focus styles).

Next
- Send your real product list (titles, prices, image filenames/URLs, descriptions) and the images â€” Iâ€™ll plug them in.
- Or tell me if you want integration with Stripe/Paystack, a headless CMS, or a Netlify/GitHub Pages deploy setup.

Below are the three files. Drop them into the same folder (put images in an images/ directory) and open index.html.

